ADMM Convex Clustering

Fan Wu

2016-07-08

Compare Clustering Performance with James and Sugar (2003)

We considered a case where ADMM-Q shows some advantage over James and Sugars method in terms of clustering performance. The clustering performance is measured by both adjusted Rands Index (ARI) and variation of information (VI). ARI ranges from 0 to 1, with 1 indicating coincidence of two clusterings; whereas VI ranges from 0 to \(n\) (sample size), with 0 indicating coincidence of two clusterings.

Simulation setting:

  • True cluster centers:
    • \(4 - 4 t^2\)
    • \(1 - t + t^2\)
    • \(4 - 8t + 4t^2\)
  • \(\sigma_b = 0.1, \sigma_e = 0.1\)

James and Sugar fit with 2 clusters

arivi <- read.csv('/media/lunch/Windows7_OS/Box Sync/lclust/data-raw/arivi_K3(2)_4,0,-4;1,-1,1;4,-8,4_b(.1)e(.1).csv', as.is = TRUE)

colMeans(arivi)
##    ARI_JS  ARI_ADMM     VI_JS   VI_ADMM 
## 0.5521204 0.9503719 0.7461802 0.1445938
apply(arivi, 2, median)
##    ARI_JS  ARI_ADMM     VI_JS   VI_ADMM 
## 0.5647059 0.9616684 0.6666667 0.1340597
apply(arivi, 2, sd)
##     ARI_JS   ARI_ADMM      VI_JS    VI_ADMM 
## 0.02003608 0.08581403 0.11421991 0.17933516
arivi.long <- melt(arivi)
ggplot(data = arivi.long[1 : nrow(arivi.long) / 2, ], aes(x = value)) + geom_histogram() + facet_wrap(~variable, nrow = 3)

ggplot(data = arivi.long[(nrow(arivi.long) / 2 + 1) : nrow(arivi.long), ], aes(x = value)) + geom_histogram() + facet_wrap(~variable, nrow = 3)

clust.idx <- cbind(melt(as.matrix(arivi[1 : 2]), value.name = "ARI"),
                   melt(as.matrix(arivi[3 : 4]),  value.name = "VI"))
clust.idx <- clust.idx[-(4:5)]
names(clust.idx)[1:2] <- c("Iter", "Method")
clust.idx$Method <- gsub("ARI_|VI_", "", clust.idx$Method)

ggplot(data = clust.idx, aes(x = ARI, y = VI, group = Iter, color = Method)) + geom_point(size = 4, alpha = 0.9, pch = 20) + theme_grey(16) + theme(legend.position="bottom")
